comment_data.body:
The simple way to update Cython code for a GIL-free world is if the locking has a similar level of scope as the GIL did. For example a per-object lock could be used when calling a method on the object or something. I would still want to opt in or out to that though because many types don't need locking (e.g. if immutable).

Perhaps something like:
```cython
cimport cython
from some_c_lib cimport read_c_data, mutate_c_data, c_function, ...

cdef class matrix:

    @cython.lock_self
    def __getitem__(self, ...):
        x = read_c_data(self.data)
        ...

    @cython.lock_self
    def __setitem__(self, ...):
        mutate_c_data(self.data, ...)
    
    def __add__(self, other):
        if type(other) != matrix:
            return NotImplemented
        with cython.lock2(self, other):
            res = c_function(self.data, other.data)
        ...

cdef class Integer:

    def __add__(self, other):
        if type(other) != Integer:
            return NotImplemented
        # Locking not needed at all here because immutable
        return c_function_int(self.data, other.data)
```
A method-level decorator for a per-object lock gives the same sort of granularity that you would have had with the GIL that `__setitem__` and `__getitem__` cannot be called simultaneously. In some situations you would need to lock other objects though and you wouldn't want to lock too early if you are just going to return e.g. `NotImplemented` (I'm assuming that `PyObject_TypeCheck` etc don't need locks).

Cython does not currently have the knowledge to know when the lock is needed because it does not know which objects are immutable or not and has no idea what is happening inside `c_function`, `mutate_c_data` etc.
